<div class="comment-meta"><span class="comment-author vcard"><cite class="fn" title="http://budcaddell.com"><a href="http://budcaddell.com" title="Bud Caddell" class="url" rel="external nofollow">Bud Caddell</a></cite></span><!-- .comment-author .vcard --> <span class="published"><abbr class="comment-date" title="Thursday, December 1st, 2011, 12:52 pm">December 1, 2011</abbr> at <abbr class="comment-time" title="Thursday, December 1st, 2011, 12:52 pm">12:52 pm</abbr></span> . <a class="permalink" href="http://whatconsumesme.com/2011/posts-ive-written/what-is-a-digital-strategy/comment-page-1/#comment-76831" title="Permalink to comment 76831">Permalink</a> </div>	</div><!-- .comment-header -->
<div class="comment-content comment-text">
<p>Thanks for the comments. I&#8217;ll try wade through them.</p>
<p>&#8220;Why, if the purpose of the digital strategy is to meet business objectives, isnâ€™t digital just built in to the greater business strategy?&#8221;</p>
<p>It absolutely should be. And planning must become one single discipline, not a fractured one. In an integrated world, the customer and culture are at the center of everything we do.</p>
<p>Brett, I have to disagree. If you want your digital strategy to be successful, it better empower and engage networks of people. Everything depends on that &#8211; even down to how brand perception is shaped (which is by networks of people).</p>
<p>Monica, you can&#8217;t shape a strategy solely by the tools at hand. In digital they change so frequently. Social media is one aspect of digital, but even banners must ultimately impact networks of people. </p>
<p>Jason, nice try but Hemingway wants a word with you. <img src="http://whatconsumesme.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif.pagespeed.ce.v_1TW3nWi5.gif" alt=":)" class="wp-smiley"/><br/>
I don&#8217;t know if you can define digital strategy using &#8220;the lens of digital&#8221; â€“ sorta short circuits itself. </p>
<p>But my definition is probably far from perfect, too.</p>
